 that dysfunctional self-related cognitions represent central factors contributing towards development maintenance mmorpg addiction high degree avatar identification found by leménager et al addicted group this study indicates that mmorpg playing may represent attempt compensate for impairments self-concept psychotherapeutic interventions should therefore focus on development coping strategies for real-life situations which addicted players tend experience themselves incompetent inferior richard bartle author designing virtual worlds classified multiplayer rpg-players into four primary psychological groups his classifications were then expanded upon by erwin andreasen who developed concept into thirty-question bartle test that helps players determine which category they are associated with with over test responses this perhaps largest ongoing survey multiplayer game players based on bartle yee's research jon radoff has published updated model player motivation that focuses on immersion competition cooperation achievement these elements may be found not only mmorpgs but many other types games within emerging field gamification world warcraft temporary design glitch attracted attention psychologists epidemiologists across north america when corrupted blood disease monster began spread unintentionally—and uncontrollably—into wider game world centers for disease control used incident research model chart both progression disease potential human response large-scale epidemic infection economics see also virtual economy user browsing market for items eve online many mmorpgs feature living economies virtual items currency have be gained through play have definite value for players such virtual economy can be analyzed using data logged by game has value economic research more significantly these virtual economies can affect economies real world one early researchers mmorpgs was edward castronova who demonstrated that supply-and-demand market exists for virtual items that crosses over with real world this crossover has some requirements game ability for players sell item each other for in-game virtual currency bartering for items between players for items similar value purchase in-game items for real-world currency exchanges real-world currencies for virtual currencies invention user-created meta-currencies such dragon kill points distribute in-game rewards idea attaching real-world value virtual items has had profound effect on players game industry even courts virtual currency selling pioneer ige received lawsuit from world warcraft player for interfering economics intended use game by selling wow gold castronova's first study found that highly liquid if illegal currency market existed with value everquest's in-game currency exceeding that japanese yen some people even make living by working these virtual economies these people are often referred gold farmers may be employed game sweatshops game publishers usually prohibit exchange real-world money for virtual goods but others actively promote idea linking directly profiting from exchange second life entropia universe virtual economy real-world economy are directly linked this means that real money can be deposited for game money vice versa real-world items have also been sold for game money entropia some players second life have generated revenues excess $100000 some issues confronting online economies include use bots automated programs that assist some players accumulating in-game wealth disadvantage other players use unsanctioned auction sites which has led publishers seek legal remedies prevent their use based on intellectual-property claims emergence virtual crime which can take form both fraud against player publisher online game even real-life acts violence stemming from in-game transactions linking real-world virtual economies rare mmorpgs generally believed be detrimental gameplay if real-world wealth can be used obtain greater more immediate rewards than skillful gameplay 